1. What Design Patterns Actually Are

	A design pattern is a general solution to a common software design problem.

	Not code.
	Not a library.
	Not a framework.

	It’s a conceptual blueprint for structuring code.

	Example problem:

	You want only one instance of a class in the entire application.

	Solution:

	Use the Singleton pattern.

2. The 3 Main Categories
	1) Creational Design Patterns
	2) Structural Design Patterns
	3) Behavioral Design Patterns


	1. Creational Design Patterns

	These patterns deal with object creation mechanisms.
	Instead of creating objects directly with new, these patterns provide flexible ways to create objects.

	why they exist
	Direct object creation can make code tightly coupled and hard to modify and hard to modify.
	Creational patterns help decouple the creation process from usage.

	Common Creational Patterns

		* Singleton – ensures only one instance of a class exists.

        * Factory Method – creates objects without exposing creation logic.

        * Abstract Factory – creates families of related objects.

        * Builder – constructs complex objects step-by-step.

        * Prototype – creates objects by cloning an existing object.

	2. Structural Design Patterns

	These patterns focus on how classes and objects are composed or structured to build larger systems.

	They help ensure components work together efficiently without tight coupling.

	Why they exist

	As applications grow, relationships between classes become complex. Structural patterns simplify those relationships.

	Common Structural Patterns

		* Adapter – converts one interface into another compatible interface.

		* Decorator – adds new functionality to objects dynamically.

		* Facade – provides a simplified interface to a complex subsystem.

		* Composite – treats individual objects and groups of objects uniformly.

		* Proxy – controls access to another object.

	3. Behavioral Design Patterns

    These patterns focus on communication and interaction between objects.

    They help manage responsibilities and behavior distribution.

    Why they exist

    Without structured communication patterns, code becomes messy with complex object dependencies.

    Common Behavioral Patterns

	    * Observer – defines a one-to-many dependency between objects.

	    * Strategy – allows interchangeable algorithms.

	    * Command – encapsulates requests as objects.

	    * State – allows an object to change behavior when its state changes.

	    * Mediator – centralizes communication between objects.

	    * Chain of Responsibility – passes requests along a chain of handlers.